      <!-- n8n -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">07 · n8n Node</div>
          <h2><code>n8n-nodes-sardis</code> — community node.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Lives at <code>packages/n8n-nodes-sardis/</code>. Ships one node
            (<code>nodes/Sardis/Sardis.node.ts</code>) plus a credential type
            (<code>credentials/SardisApi.credentials.ts</code>) that securely stores the API key in
            n8n's encrypted credential store. Requires <code>n8n-workflow ≥ 2.0</code>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre><code># Install inside an n8n instance
npm i -g n8n-nodes-sardis

# Or add via n8n Community Nodes UI: Settings → Community Nodes → Install
# Package: n8n-nodes-sardis</code></pre>
        <p class="text-muted mt-16">
          Example flow: <code>Gmail → Sardis: Request Approval → Wait → Sardis: Pay</code>.
          The <code>Sardis</code> node exposes operations for pay, hold, approve, balance,
          and webhook dispatch so the workflow can stay in one tool.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Spend widget -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">08 · Spend Widget</div>
          <h2><code>sardis-spend-widget</code> — consumer-side approval UI.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Lives at <code>packages/sardis-spend-widget/</code>. An embeddable widget that consumer
            agent apps drop in so the <em>end user</em> — not the agent — confirms spend above a
            threshold. Uses a <code>pk_live_…</code> publishable key scoped to a single session;
            sensitive operations still go through the server.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre><code>&lt;script src="https://widget.sardis.sh/v1/spend.js" async&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;sardis-spend
  publishable-key="pk_live_…"
  session-id="ss_live_abc123"
  on-approve="handleApprove"
  on-deny="handleDeny"&gt;
&lt;/sardis-spend&gt;</code></pre>
        <p class="text-muted mt-16">
          The widget subscribes over SSE to spend requests for the session and renders a native-feel
          approve/deny sheet. Complements the Telegram bot surface for users who live in a browser
          rather than in chat.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Telegram bot -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">09 · Telegram Bot</div>
          <h2><code>sardis-telegram-bot</code> — on-call surface.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Lives at <code>packages/sardis-telegram-bot/</code>. Python bot that mirrors the
            approval / balance / kill-switch surface into Telegram. Built for solo operators and
            on-call rotations who want real-time agent-spend pings in a chat they already have open.
          </p>
        </div>
        <pre><code># typical commands (the bot is side-loaded, not published)
/balance              # shows wallet balances across chains
/approvals            # lists pending approvals, with approve/deny buttons
/kill &lt;wallet&gt;     # pauses all outbound spend for a wallet
/status               # last 10 ledger decisions</code></pre>
      </section>

      <!-- Sequence: how surfaces share one API -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Shape</div>
          <h2>Nine entry points, one pipeline.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Whichever surface originates the call, the request hits the same API gateway and
            the same <code>PaymentOrchestrator</code>. This is what makes "add a new surface"
            cheap — the trust model doesn't change.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
flowchart LR
    PY["Python SDK"] --&gt; API
    TS["TS SDK"] --&gt; API
    CLI["sardis-cli (py)"] --&gt; API
    GO["sardis (go binary)"] --&gt; API
    JCLI["@sardis/cli"] --&gt; API
    MCP["@sardis/mcp-server"] --&gt; API
    N8N["n8n node"] --&gt; API
    WID["spend-widget"] --&gt; API
    TG["telegram-bot"] --&gt; API
    API["api.sardis.sh · require_principal"] --&gt; O["PaymentOrchestrator"]
    O --&gt; PP["Pre-Execution Pipeline"]
    PP --&gt; CX["Chain / Wallet / Rails"]
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Release cadence -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">10 · Release Cadence</div>
          <h2>How SDKs actually ship.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Two workflows in <code>.github/workflows/</code> drive publishing. Tag pushes trigger
            production releases; <code>workflow_dispatch</code> supports manual rc builds with a
            TestPyPI / npm prerelease toggle. No SDK version leaves CI without green tests.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Workflow</th><th>Triggers</th><th>Targets</th><th>Registries</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><code>release-python-sdk.yml</code></td>
              <td>Tag <code>py-sdk-v*</code> or manual dispatch</td>
              <td><code>packages/sardis-sdk-python</code></td>
              <td>PyPI (prod) / TestPyPI (prerelease)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>release-python-integrations.yml</code></td>
              <td>Tag <code>py-&lt;integration&gt;-v*</code></td>
              <td>sardis-langchain, sardis-crewai, sardis-autogpt, …</td>
              <td>PyPI / TestPyPI</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>release-npm.yml</code></td>
              <td>Tag <code>mcp-v*</code>, <code>sdk-js-v*</code>, <code>ai-sdk-v*</code>, <code>connect-js-v*</code></td>
              <td>MCP server, TS SDK, AI SDK, Connect JS</td>
              <td>npm</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><code>sign-artifacts.yml</code></td>
              <td>On release builds</td>
              <td>All published artifacts</td>
              <td>Sigstore attestations</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

